[[User:Immanuelle|Immanuelle]] ([[User talk:Immanuelle|talk]]) 20:51, 25 March 2025 (UTC)}}
 (Wilderness Hot Springs):  
  These are naturally occurring, undeveloped hot springs found “in the wild.” They lack formal commercial facilities and often require visitors to set up their own bathing arrangements or rely on minimal local upkeep.

* {{ill|Secret hot spring|ja|秘湯|1=Secret hot spring|12=draft|12=draft}} (Secret Hot Springs):  
  Coined around the mid‑1970s, this term refers to hot springs tucked away in remote, hard-to-reach areas (often deep in the mountains). They evoke an aura of mystery and tradition, appealing to those seeking a quiet, off‑the‑beaten‑path retreat.

* {{ill|Hidden hot spring|ja|隠し湯|12=draft|12=draft}} (Hidden Hot Springs):  
  Historically linked to feudal times, these were hot springs that local lords or elites kept exclusively for their own use, deliberately concealed from the public. Today, the term emphasizes their exclusive, almost “forbidden” allure.

* {{ill|Drawn‑off hot spring|ja|引湯|1=Drawn‐off hot spring|2=ja|3=引湯|lt=Drawn‐off hot spring|12=draft|12=draft}} (Drawn‑off Hot Springs):  
  Unlike the others that are used at the site of emergence, drawn‑off hot springs involve hot water being piped from its natural source to another location. This process often cools the water slightly and is used to distribute onsen water to developed bathing facilities.

Each term reflects a different aspect—whether it’s the natural setting, historical secrecy, or the method of utilization.

[[User:Immanuelle|Immanuelle]] ([[User talk:Immanuelle|talk]]) 20:59, 25 March 2025 (UTC)}}

[[File:白馬鑓温泉露天風呂Img091.jpg|thumb|right|220px|A hot spring accessible only to mountaineers, {{ill|Hakuba Yari Onsen|ja|白馬鑓温泉|12=draft|12=draft}} is located on the mid-slope of Mount Hakuba Yari at an elevation of 2,100 m.]]

'''Hitō''' (秘湯) refers to hot springs that are typically located deep in the mountains or in areas with poor access that were once described as {{ill|isolated island|ja|陸の孤島|12=draft|12=draft}}, and which include secret springs used by ancient rulers or {{ill|Shugendō practitioner|ja|修験者|12=draft|12=draft}}—that is, hot springs that quietly emerge in hidden, remote regions.<ref>{{Cite web|Japanese source|title=What is the definition of Hitō? Famous examples? - Hot Spring Encyclopedia - BIGLOBE Onsen|url=https://travel.biglobe.ne.jp/onsen/jiten/ninki_07.html|website=BIGLOBE Travel|accessdate=2021-02-01|language=ja}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|Japanese source|title=The meaning of Hitō (秘湯) - goo Dictionary|url=https://dictionary.goo.ne.jp/word/%E7%A7%98%E6%B9%AF/|website=goo Dictionary|accessdate=2021-02-01|language=ja}}</ref><ref name=":0">{{Cite web|Japanese source|title=About the Japan Secret Hot Springs Preservation Association - Official Website|url=https://www.hitou.or.jp/|website=Japan Secret Hot Springs Preservation Association|accessdate=2021-02-01|language=ja}}</ref><ref name=":1">{{Cite web|Japanese source|title=Greeting from the Honorary President - Japan Secret Hot Springs Preservation Association Official Website|url=https://www.hitou.or.jp/|website=Japan Secret Hot Springs Preservation Association|accessdate=2021-02-01|language=ja}}</ref>.

"Hitō" was a coined term created around {{ill|1975|ja|1975th year|12=draft|12=draft}}, and its originator was the proponent of establishing the {{ill|Japan Secret Hot Springs Preservation Association|ja|日本秘湯を守る会|12=draft|12=draft}}, {{ill|Iwakki Hifumi|ja|岩木一二三|12=draft|12=draft}} (born in Showa 2, died in Heisei 13). He founded {{ill|Asahi Travel|ja|株式会社朝日旅行会|lt=Asahi Travel Company|lt_ja=株式会社朝日旅行会|12=draft|12=draft}} in 1965 (Showa 40). In the mid‑Showa 40s, when hot springs were equated with entertainment districts and far removed from the true spirit of travel, he carried a deep nostalgia—evoked by the sight of repatriation ships after the war and the notion of “a country in ruins but with enduring mountains and rivers”—and set out across the nation in search of quiet mountain hot spring inns where one might reflect on life in solitude. Inspired by these experiences and sentiments, he established the “Hitō Hiking Association” in 1972 (Showa 47) to help people rediscover the true essence of travel through journeys on rugged mountain paths and visits to humble hot spring inns.

== Overview ==
[[File:鹿の湯（しかのゆ）露天風呂（大）P6270560.jpg|thumb|left|150px|Open-air baths are scattered along a mountain stream in the primeval forests of Hokkaido at {{ill|Shikanoyu|ja|鹿の湯|12=draft|12=draft}}]]
Although many hot spring enthusiasts have long sought secluded onsens deep in the mountains, this trend became more widespread after the {{ill|Japanese post-war economic miracle|ja|高度成長期|12=draft|12=draft}}. As {{ill|hot spring inns|ja|温泉宿|12=draft|12=draft}} began to be used for company outings, and major hot spring resorts—such as {{ill|Arima Hot Spring|ja|有馬温泉|lt=Arima|lt_ja=有馬|12=draft|12=draft}}, {{ill|Atami|ja|熱海|12=draft|12=draft}}, and {{ill|Beppu Hot Spring|ja|別府温泉|lt=Beppu|lt_ja=別府|12=draft|12=draft}}—transformed into entertainment districts ({{ill|entertainment district|ja|歓楽地|12=draft|12=draft}}), hot spring enthusiasts in search of the simple, therapeutic atmosphere of traditional bathing resorts increasingly turned to remote or smaller onsens. It is said that the term “Hitō” began to be used around this time.

During the {{ill|1960s|ja|1960th year 代|12=draft|12=draft}}, manga artist {{ill|Yoshiharu Tsuge|ja|つげ義春|12=draft|12=draft}} frequently visited rustic, offbeat therapeutic hot spring resorts ({{ill|Therapeutic hot spring resort|ja|湯治場|12=draft|12=draft}}), capturing their unique ambiance in many works and travel sketches.<ref name="asahi">Asahi Graph, February 14, 1959</ref> Moreover, Tsuge’s influence on many Hitō enthusiasts was considerable.

In the {{ill|1980s|ja|1980th year 代|12=draft|12=draft}}, a Hitō boom emerged, as more people favored humble, single‐room mountain inns over large resorts with entertainment districts. This trend led to the popularization of Hitō; even the once‑rustic inns began incorporating modern amenities (such as showers ({{ill|shower|ja|シャワー|12=draft|12=draft}}) and flush toilets ({{ill|flush toilet|ja|水洗トイレ|12=draft|12=draft}})), thus becoming somewhat commercialized. Today, reaching an authentic Hitō often requires a long, arduous hike.

== Major Hitō in Japan ==
[[File:Takamagahara Hot Spring.jpg|thumb|right|220px|At an elevation of 2,100 m. Approximately 13 hours on foot to reach {{ill|Takamagahara Hot Spring|ja|高天原温泉|12=draft|12=draft}} ({{ill|Toyama Prefecture|ja|富山県|12=draft|12=draft}}, {{ill|Toyama City|ja|富山市|12=draft|12=draft}}).]]
Although what exactly qualifies as “Hitō” remains open to debate, here is a tentative list of hot springs set in remote, almost otherworldly locations:

* {{ill|Takamagahara Hot Spring|ja|高天原温泉|12=draft|12=draft}} ({{ill|Toyama Prefecture|ja|富山県|12=draft|12=draft}}, {{ill|Toyama City|ja|富山市|12=draft|12=draft}}) – elevation 2,100 m; approximately 13 hours on foot.
* {{ill|Sennin Onsen|ja|仙人温泉|12=draft|12=draft}} ({{ill|Toyama Prefecture|ja|富山県|12=draft|12=draft}} {{ill|Kurobe City|ja|黒部市|12=draft|12=draft}}) – elevation 1,550 m; approximately 8 hours on foot.
* {{ill|Asohara Onsen|ja|阿曽原温泉|12=draft|12=draft}} ({{ill|Toyama Prefecture|ja|富山県|12=draft|12=draft}} {{ill|Kurobe City|ja|黒部市|12=draft|12=draft}}) – elevation 900 m; approximately 5 hours on foot.
* {{ill|Hakuba Yari Onsen|ja|白馬鑓温泉|12=draft|12=draft}} ({{ill|Nagano Prefecture|ja|長野県|12=draft|12=draft}}, {{ill|Kitaazumi District|ja|北安曇郡|12=draft|12=draft}}, {{ill|Hakuba Village|ja|白馬村|12=draft|12=draft}}) – elevation 2,100 m; approximately 4–5 hours on foot.
* {{ill|Akadake Mineral Spring|ja|赤岳鉱泉|12=draft|12=draft}} ({{ill|Nagano Prefecture|ja|長野県|12=draft|12=draft}}, {{ill|Chino City|ja|茅野市|12=draft|12=draft}}) – elevation 2,240 m; approximately 3 hours on foot.
* {{ill|Nakadake Onsen|ja|中岳温泉|12=draft|12=draft}} ({{ill|Hokkaido|ja|北海道|12=draft|12=draft}}, {{ill|Kamikawa District|ja|上川郡 (石狩国)|lt=Kamikawa District|lt_ja=上川郡|12=draft|12=draft}}, {{ill|Higashikawa Town|ja|東川町|12=draft|12=draft}}) – elevation 1,840 m; approximately 2 hours on foot.
* {{ill|Kurogane Onsen|ja|くろがね温泉|12=draft|12=draft}} ({{ill|Fukushima Prefecture|ja|福島県|12=draft|12=draft}}, {{ill|Nihonmatsu City|ja|二本松市|12=draft|12=draft}}) – elevation 1,400 m; approximately 2 hours on foot.
* {{ill|Honzawa Onsen|ja|本沢温泉|12=draft|12=draft}} ({{ill|Nagano Prefecture|ja|長野県|12=draft|12=draft}}, {{ill|Minamisaku District|ja|南佐久郡|12=draft|12=draft}}, {{ill|Nammoku Village|ja|南牧村 (長野県)|lt=Nammoku Village|lt_ja=南牧村|12=draft|12=draft}}) – elevation 2,150 m; approximately 2 hours on foot.

All of these locations require mountaineering equipment.

