*{{ill|Secret hot spring|ja|秘湯|1=Secret hot spring|12=draft|12=draft}}
*{{ill|Hidden hot spring|ja|隠し湯|12=draft|12=draft}}
*{{ill|Drawn‐off hot spring|ja|引湯|1=Drawn‐off hot spring|2=ja|3=引湯|lt=Drawn‐off hot spring|12=draft|12=draft}}
[[User:Immanuelle|Immanuelle]] ([[User talk:Immanuelle|talk]]) 20:51, 25 March 2025 (UTC)}}
 (Wilderness Hot Springs):  
  These are naturally occurring, undeveloped hot springs found “in the wild.” They lack formal commercial facilities and often require visitors to set up their own bathing arrangements or rely on minimal local upkeep.

* {{ill|Secret hot spring|ja|秘湯|1=Secret hot spring|12=draft|12=draft}} (Secret Hot Springs):  
  Coined around the mid‑1970s, this term refers to hot springs tucked away in remote, hard-to-reach areas (often deep in the mountains). They evoke an aura of mystery and tradition, appealing to those seeking a quiet, off‑the‑beaten‑path retreat.

* {{ill|Hidden hot spring|ja|隠し湯|12=draft|12=draft}} (Hidden Hot Springs):  
  Historically linked to feudal times, these were hot springs that local lords or elites kept exclusively for their own use, deliberately concealed from the public. Today, the term emphasizes their exclusive, almost “forbidden” allure.

* {{ill|Drawn‑off hot spring|ja|引湯|1=Drawn‐off hot spring|2=ja|3=引湯|lt=Drawn‐off hot spring|12=draft|12=draft}} (Drawn‑off Hot Springs):  
  Unlike the others that are used at the site of emergence, drawn‑off hot springs involve hot water being piped from its natural source to another location. This process often cools the water slightly and is used to distribute onsen water to developed bathing facilities.

Each term reflects a different aspect—whether it’s the natural setting, historical secrecy, or the method of utilization.

[[User:Immanuelle|Immanuelle]] ([[User talk:Immanuelle|talk]]) 20:59, 25 March 2025 (UTC)}}

[[File:白馬鑓温泉露天風呂Img091.jpg|thumb|right|220px|A hot spring accessible only to mountaineers, {{ill|Hakuba Yari Onsen|ja|白馬鑓温泉|12=draft|12=draft}} is located on the mid-slope of Mount Hakuba Yari at an elevation of 2,100 m.]]

'''Hitō''' (秘湯) refers to hot springs that are typically located deep in the mountains or in areas with poor access that were once described as {{ill|isolated island|ja|陸の孤島|12=draft|12=draft}}, and which include secret springs used by ancient rulers or {{ill|Shugendō practitioner|ja|修験者|12=draft|12=draft}}—that is, hot springs that quietly emerge in hidden, remote regions.<ref>{{Cite web|Japanese source|title=What is the definition of Hitō? Famous examples? - Hot Spring Encyclopedia - BIGLOBE Onsen|url=https://travel.biglobe.ne.jp/onsen/jiten/ninki_07.html|website=BIGLOBE Travel|accessdate=2021-02-01|language=ja}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|Japanese source|title=The meaning of Hitō (秘湯) - goo Dictionary|url=https://dictionary.goo.ne.jp/word/%E7%A7%98%E6%B9%AF/|website=goo Dictionary|accessdate=2021-02-01|language=ja}}</ref><ref name=":0">{{Cite web|Japanese source|title=About the Japan Secret Hot Springs Preservation Association - Official Website|url=https://www.hitou.or.jp/|website=Japan Secret Hot Springs Preservation Association|accessdate=2021-02-01|language=ja}}</ref><ref name=":1">{{Cite web|Japanese source|title=Greeting from the Honorary President - Japan Secret Hot Springs Preservation Association Official Website|url=https://www.hitou.or.jp/|website=Japan Secret Hot Springs Preservation Association|accessdate=2021-02-01|language=ja}}</ref>.

"Hitō" was a coined term created around {{ill|1975|ja|1975th year|12=draft|12=draft}}, and its originator was the proponent of establishing the {{ill|Japan Secret Hot Springs Preservation Association|ja|日本秘湯を守る会|12=draft|12=draft}}, {{ill|Iwakki Hifumi|ja|岩木一二三|12=draft|12=draft}} (born in Showa 2, died in Heisei 13). He founded {{ill|Asahi Travel|ja|株式会社朝日旅行会|lt=Asahi Travel Company|lt_ja=株式会社朝日旅行会|12=draft|12=draft}} in 1965 (Showa 40). In the mid‑Showa 40s, when hot springs were equated with entertainment districts and far removed from the true spirit of travel, he carried a deep nostalgia—evoked by the sight of repatriation ships after the war and the notion of “a country in ruins but with enduring mountains and rivers”—and set out across the nation in search of quiet mountain hot spring inns where one might reflect on life in solitude. Inspired by these experiences and sentiments, he established the “Hitō Hiking Association” in 1972 (Showa 47) to help people rediscover the true essence of travel through journeys on rugged mountain paths and visits to humble hot spring inns.

